Engineering, Inc. to conduct traffic signal timing analysis at three intersections along Brainard Road,
Cedar Road (1), I-271 NB Exit/Entrance Ramp (2), and the I-271 SB Exit Ramp (3), a length
approximately 1200’. A location map for the study area is shown in Figure-1 below:

The purpose of this study is to evaluate and recommend signal timing changes to improve signal
coordination on Brainard Road and to reduce queues on the I-271NB exit/entrance ramp, that occur as
part of daily recurring congestion. A secondary goal of this study is to reduce the frequency and
severity of crashes at these three intersections by improving signal timings.
Land use immediately north and south of the study area is residential. The interchange of I-271 is
within the study area. Exit ramps for both I-271SB and I-271NB are located on Brainard Road. The
entrance ramp for I-271NB is located on Brainard Road, while the entrance ramp for I-271SB is located
on Cedar Road west of Brainard. Multiple traffic generators are located on or immediately adjacent to
Cedar Road. The commercial developments, Legacy Village and Beachwood place, are located on
Cedar Road west of the study area, while business parks are located on Landerbrook Drive and Lander
The posted speed limit is 35 mph on Brainard Road, 35 mph on Cedar Road, and 60 mph on I-271.

Traffic modeling and analysis software, Synchro V8 and Simtraffic, was used for the signal operation
analyses. Three models were designed for three different peak conditions:
For signalized intersections, Synchro calculates the Level of Service (LOS) for the intersection in terms
of the average total delay per vehicle. The total delay is the sum of control delay and queue delay.
Control delay is the component of delay caused by the downstream control device and is calculated
using the Percentile Delay Method. Queue delay is an analysis of the affects of queues and blocking on
short links and short turning bays. LOS is defined in terms of delay and is a measure of driver
discomfort and intersection performance with respect to vehicular capacity and quality of service
provided to road users. Delay refers to total average stopped delay experienced by motorists at the
referenced intersection. The level of service is classified into six different levels, ranging from A to F.
Table 1 shows the definitions of each level.

Based upon the results of the 24-hour traffic volumes, a morning timing plan is recommended
between 6:30 AM and 9:00 AM, a midday program between 9:00 AM and 3:00 PM, and an evening
timing plan between 3:00 PM and 7:00 PM. The existing turning movement counts at each of the
signalized intersections are provided in Appendix A.
A vehicular change (yellow time) and clearance interval (all red time) check was completed for each
phase of the Brainard Road signal system. Calculations are based on the ODOT Traffic Engineering
Manual (TEM), Section 403-2 (revised 7/22/2012) and utilize approach speed and crossing street width
measured from the stop line to the far edge of the conflicting travel lane or the far edge of the
pedestrian crossing. Recommendations are based on the TEM as well as field observations.
Recommendations for all-red time take into account a one second vehicle start-up time. Existing,
calculated, recommended yellow change, and all-red clearance interval times can be seen in Table 2.

software programs for the four timing plans. The four different timing plans are the AM peak, midday

PM peaks. Proposed timings are based on traffic data, field observations, and input received from
ODOT and the local jurisdictions. A description is provided below.

Alternate 1 provided for southbound leading and lagging protected left-turn phasing on Brainard Road
at Cedar Road. Also, the northbound left-turn phase on Brainard Road at Cedar Road is a leading
protected phase. At the time of analysis, it was believed that it may be physically impossible to
operate both southbound and northbound left turns at the same time without vehicle paths
overlapping. Therefore, Alternate 2 has a southbound leading protected left-turn phase and a
northbound lagging protected left-turn phase while Alternate 4 has a southbound lagging protected
left-turn phase and a northbound leading protect left-turn phase. It was later determined that both
southbound and northbound could be operated simultaneously with current intersection geometry.

page.text: Turning movements and driver behavior are similar during the weekday midday peak to those during
the weekend peaks based on field observations. Tube count information indicated that on Brainard
Road, Saturday and Sunday volumes are similar to each other yet are less than the midday peak
volumes. On the I-271 NB ramps, Sunday volumes are less than Saturday volumes. Specifically on the
loop ramp (I-271 NB to Cedar westbound traffic), Saturday and Sunday volumes are higher than
DLZ utilized turning movement counts collected during the midday to develop coordination timings.
The current cycle length for midday is 150 seconds. DLZ recommends a preferred midday alternate
with a 130 second cycle. This preferred midday alternate is based on the same parameters (signal
phasing) as Alternate 1 in the PM peak hour.
Saturdays currently operate the same time of day schedule as a standard weekday while Sundays run
free (no coordination). Based on collected weekend traffic volumes, DLZ recommends utilizing the
proposed midday timing plan on Saturdays from 9:00 AM to 7:00 PM, and Sundays from 10:00 AM to
6:00 PM and allowing the signals to run free the rest of the weekend.

With the Alternate 1 recommended signal modifications at the Brainard Road and Cedar Road
intersection and signal retiming along Brainard Road at the intersections of Cedar Road, the I-271NB
ramps, and the I-271SB exit ramp, total delay through the study section was reduced. The delay for I-
271NB exiting vehicles has been reduced and the observed queuing onto the freeway has been
significantly reduced/eliminated in both the AM and PM peak hours. Travel time for northbound
Brainard Road improved in all peak periods.
However, in an effort to balance the delays throughout the study area, some movements on
southbound Brainard Road experienced slight increases in delay. After coordinating signals in the PM
for the I-271NB left-turn movement to northbound Brainard, travel time increased for I-271SB exiting
vehicles traveling SB Brainard to westbound Cedar Road and for vehicles turning left onto northbound
The overall travel time results of the midday peak showed a slight change in travel time and delay.
Only two movements were analyzed for the midday peak period, northbound and southbound
Brainard Road, with the southbound movement showing an increase in delay and northbound showing
a decrease in delay as shown in Table 10. The Synchro analysis for the midday period showed a 15%
reduction in delay for the three intersections and is a better representation of the overall
improvement than the two travel time studies (NB and SB Brainard Road) because in takes into
account other critical movements along the study area (turning movements off I-271 NB&SB).
Since the new signal timings (as well as the Pre-Study signal timings) do not accommodate some of the
pedestrian clearance times crossing Brainard Road, certain traffic signals will go out of coordination for
a few cycles in order to accommodate the pedestrian actuation. This did not show as being a problem
for progression along Brainard in the optimized (After) travel time studies due to the low pedestrian
traffic at the intersection of Cedar Road (7 pedestrians counted for a 9 hour count).
It is important to recognize that proper signal system operation is highly dependent on maintenance of
communication and detection equipment. Faulty detection can lead to unnecessary delays. It is
recommended that the system equipment is checked for proper operation every 30 days to 60 days.
